hopobject.body: A staff restaurant myglobalmed.net "Men are more likely to be concentrated in higher-paying jobs. Women are more likely to be concentrated in lower-paying jobs," says Fatima Goss Graves, vice president for education and employment at the National Women's Law Center. She points out that women make up nearly two-thirds of all minimum-wage workers. The 77 percent figure is meaningful, she says, because it reflects this "occupational segregation."
